The hard left vote is capped and 53.94% of the votes in the first electoral round went to parties that are not considered leftists (anything right of the social democrats of the old Conertacion). Of the votes that Provoste got, 80% might go to Boric, but 20% of the left-center DC won't. We can split that 10% won't vote, 10% for Kast. Sichel's Vote, 80% will go for Kast, 0% Boric, 20% won't vote. Artes votes will be 95% Boric and 5% most likelt won't vote (extremely hard left). of MEO, 90% for Boric and 10% won't vote. Parisi, 70% Kast, 10% Boric and 20% won't vote.

In the 2000s history shows a duopoly between a left wing and a right wing candidate, giving Boric a chance due to the current right wing president. Whether the popularity of Narvaez for PS will split the left wing vote is an interesting dilemma and new poling will show its salience.

Provoste's announced candidacy may make this question a little more complicated. Her previous poll numbers weren't as strong as the top two but appeared to be in the upper tier of (primary) candidates: https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-07-23/center-left-candidate-jumps-into-chile-presidential-race, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_2021_Chilean_presidential_election

My reading of the political situation is that the Chilean electorate is ready to upturn the establishment, reject the status quo and introduce a progressive administration. Having said that, there appears to be a rejection of the extremes of the political spectrum. Support for the right-wing coalition had fallen to 24% of the vote for President Sebastián Piñera in a recent election and the loss of many municipalities that had traditionally voted for the right and considered an indictment of the centre right who blocked progressive reforms. Only 40% of the vote went to the establishment candidates and 60% to independents and/or newcomers. There is a demand for a rewriting of Pinochet’s constitution, during his military rule, the dismissal of government backed candidates in these elections plus the election of two-thirds of the Independent and opposition candidates will enable a new constitution. Pinera has stated that his government and the other traditional parties are attuned to the populace. Boric would appear to be at the forefront of this progressive movement, while Sichel is an independent and considered a centrist but difficulty to position politically. Of the other potential candidates José Antonio Kast is possibly too right wing and Yasna Provoste Campillay who is also centrist but may be considered part of the establishment given her long career in government.

This forecast is based on : *Boric wins 1M voices last Sunday, *His strong students supporters in streets. *the Common Force movement gave its support to Boric, after he beat Marcelo Díaz in a plebiscite held on May 27-28.
